Section 0: Introduction & Goals¶

This report will explore the complex relationship of factors related to the chosen y-variable Poor.Health (the poor health index).

Investigative Questions¶

We will explore several key areas:

  1. Quality of Care: How does a county's level of access to healthcare affect the health index?

  2. Environmental Factors: How do environmental factors (such as unemployment rate, median household income, or education levels) vary across counties with different health indices? How do these variables correlate with the health index at a county level? How do these environmental variables relate with the quality of care in a county?

  3. Behavioral Factors: How do behavioral factors (which include obesity rates, smoking, drinking, etc.) correlate with the Health Index at a county level? Is there any socioeconomic relationship between behavioral factors and enviromental factors?

  4. Demographic/Political Factors: Are there any notable relationships between a county's health index and demographic/political variables? While the primary focus is the health index, is there any observable relationship between the political leaning of a county in the 2016 Election and its Health Index?

Hypothesis¶

My initial hypothesis is that socioeconomic environmental factors, particularly median household income, will have the strongest correlation with the health index. The median household income will likely influence certain behavioral and demographic variables (like smoking, drinking, sufficient sleeping rates) that are closely linked with certain health outcomes; in this way, median household income will act as a confounding factor on other variables that affect the poor health index.

Objective¶

Our primary objective is to identify which of these contexts—quality of care, environmental, behavioral, and demographic—exert the most substantial impact on the Poor Health Index, which may be used to provide insights for future targeted health interventions and policy planning.

Let's use a correlation matrix to get a preliminary visualization of the correlations between our dataset x-variables. This will help us determine which variables we may want to consider in our exploration of the dataset. We will look for variables with strong correlations (near 1 or -1, i.e. the very light or very darkly colored squared) in the heatmap.

Some variables with strong correlations that we may want to analyze include

  • Quality of Care: Uninsured, Primary.Care.Physicians.Per.1000
  • Environmental: Median.Household.Income
  • Behavioral: Excessive.Drinking, Physical.Inactivity, Insufficient.Sleep, Proportion.of.Smokers, Adult.Obesity
  • Demographic/Political: Life.Expectancy

This initial analysis of the dataset suggests that behavioral determinants of health appear to have the most effect on the poor health index of a county. It is also important to note that these correlations do not necessarily indicate causation; some of these variables like Life.Expectancy are inherently linked to the health index evaluation of a county, as a lower poor health index (i.e. better health outcomes) would suggest a higher life expectancy in a county.

This appears to support my initial hypothesis that Median.Household.Income will have a strong correlation with the poor health index and the other independent variables in the dataset.

Since our analysis will focus primarily on the Health.Index,Quintile and Median.Income.Quintile variables, let's quantize these two variables for easier analysis later on.

We will create two new columns that describe the health index and median income in terms of quintiles. The 0-20% bracket represents the highest 20% of values and the 80-100% bracket represents the smallest 20% of values in the distribution. For example, the 0-20% category of Poor.Health represents the top 20% poor health index values (i.e. counties with worst health) and the 80-100% category represents the bottom 20% smallest health index values (i.e. counties with best health). Similarly, the 0-20% category of Median.Household.Income represents the bottom 20% of the income distribution (lowest income counties) and the 80-100% category represents the top 20% (highest income counties).

Section 2: Exploratory Data Analysis¶

2.1 Quality of Care¶

In this section, we will explore the relationship between a county's access to health care and the poor health index.

My initial hypothesis was that areas with poor access to health care would have a lower poor health index; as access to care is more difficult to obtain, people in the county are less likely to obtain things like preventative care and timely urgent care which decreases the overall health outcomes of the county. I also hypothesized that a county's access to health care is likely to be highly related to a county's socioeconomic status, as U.S. health insurance provision is often tied to employment.

First, let's visualize the relationship between the poor health index and each of the predictor variables related to health care access.

The variable containing the most distribution stratification is the uninsurance rate. As a county's poor health index decreases (i.e. the county's health outcomes improve), the median uninsured rate of the county population noticeably decreases. Additionally, the variance in the uninsurance rate tends to decrease as the poor health index decreases as well.

There surprisingly does not exist a significantly noticeable difference in the unimodal peaks of the mental health or primary care physician rate, but the physician rate distributions are more positively skewed in "healthier" counties.

When analyzing the graphs, remember that 80-100% represents the lowest 20% of the poor health index (best health) and 0-20% is the top 20% of poor health index (worst health). 80-100% of median income is lowest 20% income bracket (poorer), and 0-20% is the highest 20% income bracket (richer).

2.2 Environmental Social Determinants of Health¶

In this section, we will explore the relationship between environmental social deterinants of health with the county-level health index. My hypothesis focuses on the importance of the Median.Household.Income as a proxy for the socioeconomic status of a county; the correlation matrix from section 1 and the analysis of uninsurance in section 2.1 also suggest that Median.Household.Income will be an important predictor of the poor health index.

Remember 80-100% is lowest health index best health, 0-20% is worst health. 80-100% of income is lowest income, 0-20% is best health.

Let's look at Median.Household.Income and Unemployment as representative views of a county's economic status.

Interestingly, the unemployment rate of the middle quintiles health index counties are all pretty similar; the top quintil sees a very large shift to the left with a significantly lower average unemployment rate, and the bottom quintile is noticeably more variant than the others. This suggests that the middle health index quintiles are distinguished by some other factors, while the top and bottom can generally be distringuished by their abnormally high/low unemployment rates.

As hypothesized, the poor health index tends to decrease as the median household income increases (i.e. approach the top 20%, or the 0-20% income quantile). There is a clear decrease in the median health index score as household income increases.

Additionally, we see that the skew of the positive tail of the overall health index distribution consists almost entirely with samples from the lowest income quantile. The variance of health index distribution also decreases as income increases.

This further cements the idea of a socioeconomic factor (like median income and the likely employment-based uninsurace rate) contributing to a county's poor health index that was first suggested in Section 2.1.

We've seen how increased median household income leads to better health outcomes and lower uninsurance rates. To further explore how the relationship between median household income and uninsurance rates affects the poor health index, the graph below shows the relationship between uninsurance and the health index when accounting for the median income quintile.

Within the general trend of increasing uninsurance leaading to poorer health, we see that as uninsurance increases the poor health index tends to increase within each of the income quintiles. Additionally, each of the stratified trend lines appear to have a shallower slope than the overall general trend line (suggesting that income differences account for some of the variation that we attributed to uninsurance). The trend line of the bottom quintile (80-100%) is relatively flat despite changes in the uninsurance rate, suggesting that median income might have "more" of an effect than uninsurance on the health index for low-income counties.

In order to truly analyze the effects of median household income and health care access (in the form of uninsurance) on health outcomes, we will perform a regression analysis on Poor.Health, Median.Household.Income, Uninsured, and the interaction betwen Median.Household.Income and Uninsured.

The outputs of the OLS regression test has:

  • R-squared (0.531): this suggests that approximately 53.1% of the variability in Poor.Health can be explained by the model.
  • Coefficients
    • Q('Median.Household.Income') (-1.034e-06): suggests a small negative association between Median.Household.Income and Poor.Health.
    • Uninsured (0.7479): suggests a positive association between the county-level uninsurance rate and Poor.Health.
    • Q('Median.Household.Income'):Uninsured (-1.083e-05): the interaction term suggests a negative relationship between median household income and the uninsurance rate. This aligns with previous analysis, where increasing income saw a decrease in uninsurance.
  • p-values: All the predictors have small p-values (less than 0.05), indicating that the predictors are statistically significant

Overall, this OLS test suggests that the uninsured rate has the largest practical influence on the poor health index, indicating that the effect of median household income on the uninsurance rate is what allows it to influence the poor health index.

2.3 Behavioral Social Determinants of Health¶

This section will explore behavioral social determinants of health and how they correlate with the health index. Behavioral factors include obesity rates, smoking, excess drinking, and insufficient sleeping, all of which are generally acknowledged contributers to poor health. The correlation matrix from section 1 suggests that Excessive.Drinking and Physical.Inactivity may have the largest correlations with the health index and the other predictor variables.

Remember 80-100% is lowest health index best health, 0-20% is worst health. 80-100% of income is lowest income, 0-20% is best health.

Since each of the behavioral variables in this category are widely associated with poor health outcomes, I decided to quickly analyze the general trends between each of these behavioral variables with the Poor.Health index and Median.Household.Income (as these are two variables that were deemed significant for socioeconomic representation in previous sections).

Most of the trends are as expected: higher rates of county-level obesity, smoking, insufficient sleep, and physical inactivity are generally seen with a higher poor health index. Additionally, an increase in these variables are associated with a decrease in median household income; this is understandable as a decrease in median household income is also associated with an increase in the poor health index.

The most surprisingly trend is in the Excessive.Drinking cateogry; an increase in excessive drinking was associated with an increased median household income and a decreased poor health index. This suggests that folks with higher and more disposable income are more likely to participate in excessive drinking; however, their higher median income will also explain the decrease in their poor health index. There is also an interesting noticeable outlier of counties with a low amount of Excessive Drinking (~0.10) and a small poor health index (~0.1).

To further explore this surprising association, the plots of the excessive drinking and smoking proportions of the population when accounting for county health index and median income are shown below.

The relationship between smoking, income, and health index is as expected: unhealthy counties with higher health indices had higher proportions of smokers and a lower median income. Excessive drinking had an opposing trend: healthier counties with lower poor health indices had higher proportions of excessive drinking and a generally high median income quintile. The explanation of a high median income potentially acting as a confounding factor between good health outcomes and excessive drinking may be at play.

When analyzing the graphs, remember that 80-100% represents the lowest 20% of the poor health index (best health) and 0-20% is the top 20% of poor health index (worst health). 80-100% of median income is lowest 20% income bracket (poorer), and 0-20% is the highest 20% income bracket (richer).

2.4 Demographic/Political Determinants of Health¶

This section will explore any notable relationships involving a county's demographic/political characteristics as determinants of health.

First, let's view the relationship between the demographic variables with the Poor.Health and Median.Household.Income variables to see if there are any interesting factors that we may not have previously considered. There does not appear to be an extremely strong correlation or surprisingly trends in most of the cases. The Over.65 and Life.Expectancy variables have a slight negative correlation with the poor health index; this is sensible as an increase in life expectancy can itself be a measurement of good health outcomes within a community. The strange decrease in income (with a trend towards an decent health index) of male-skewed counties are also likely just outliers of special communities like military base – which may contain a lot of male soldiers of decent physical health receiving average pay.

When analyzing the graphs, remember that 80-100% represents the lowest 20% of the poor health index (best health) and 0-20% is the top 20% of poor health index (worst health). 80-100% of median income is lowest 20% income bracket (poorer), and 0-20% is the highest 20% income bracket (richer).

As median household income was shown to be strongly correlated with the health index in previous sections and is thought to play a significant role in the political leanings of an individual, let's analyze the poor health distribution of each party when stratified by income.

Unsurprisingly, the poor health index decreases as median income increases. Within each bracket, Democratic counties tended to have a higher median poor health index and larger positive skews within their poor health distributions. This is reflected in the violin plot of poor health distribution across all income brackets; the democratic counties have a much larger positive skew than the Republicans. This difference can likely be attributed to some sort of confounding demographic factor like location (as Democratic counties are often concentrated in deeply urban areas).

Now, we will use cost-complexity pruning to obtain a decision tree with an optimal score on the test dataset. The best alpha parameter (which is used to balance the depth/complexity of the tree to prevent overfitting on the training data) is 3.5168960230991124e-06 with a test score of 75.21697%. However, this tree has a depth of 8 which is too large to clearly print and visualize in a jupyter notebook or HTML file.

In [ ]:
# section 2: fit the tree using cost complexity pruning
from sklearn import tree

reg_tree_model = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor()
path = reg_tree_model.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

rgrs = []
for ccp_alpha in ccp_alphas:
    rgr = tree.DecisionTreeRegressor(random_state=0, ccp_alpha=ccp_alpha)
    rgr.fit(X_train, y_train)
    rgrs.append(rgr)

train_scores = [rgr.score(X_train, y_train) for rgr in rgrs]
test_scores = [rgr.score(X_test, y_test) for rgr in rgrs]

best_alpha = ccp_alphas[np.argmax(test_scores)]
print("Best alpha: ", best_alpha)
print("Best test score: ", np.max(test_scores))

Best alpha:  3.5168960230991124e-06
Best test score:  0.7521697245759132

best_test_idx = pd.Series(test_scores).idxmax()

print("Best Tree Train Score: ", train_scores[best_test_idx])
print("Best Tree Depth: ", rgrs[best_test_idx].get_depth())

For a better visualization, we will re-train a tree using the calculated alpha parameter value above and a depth of 3. The retrained-tree has a lower test accuracy of 64.89173%, but is more interpretable and simplified.

This tree validates my hypothesis that Median.Household.Income is a significantly important determinant of the poor health index; median income is used as the separating criteria in the root node and the first node on the left path. Other criteria used by the tree include Life.Expectancy, Over.65, Insufficient.Sleep, Proportion.of.Smokers and Uninsured.

The tree also supports some of my earlier conclusions. For example:

  • high median household income, high life expectancy, and low uninsurance rates are predictive of a low poor health index
  • low median household income, with low over-65 populations or high insufficient-sleep populations lead to high poor health indices

Section 5: Summary¶

Recap of Goals and Investigative Questions¶

Our analysis began with a set of targeted questions centered around four key contexts: Quality of Care, Environmental, Behavioral, and Demographic. These questions related to potential factors influencing the poor health index of a county.

Key Findings and Conclusions¶

  1. Quality of Care: We found that while counties with better health outcomes (lower health index) generally had better access to health care services in the form of a slightly higher primary care and mental health physician presence, the distinguishing variable between counties of different health indices was the uninsured rate.

  2. Environmental Factors: As hypothesized, counties with higher median incomes had lower poor health indices. There is also a storng tie between health insurance with employment/income: counties with higher median incomes generally saw lower uninsured ratios and lower poor health indices. An OLS regression test between the poor health index, median income, and uninsurance rate found that the uninsurance rate had the highest effect on the poor health index, but both income and uninsurance were statistically significant factors in determining the health index.

  3. Behavioral Factors: Most of the negative behavioral factors like obesity, smoking, and insufficient sleep saw a positive correlation with the poor health index and a negative correlation with median household income. The excessive drinking variable surprisingly correlated with a higher median household income and a lower poor health index; the excessive drinking outlier likely has a confounding socioeconomic explanation in its relationship with higher median income.

  4. Demographic/Political Factors: There weren't any particularly strong correlations that were investigated in this section. Overall, there seemed to be a small relationship between a county's political leaning and its health index, but this relationship could potentially also be explained by a confounding socioeconomic factor like median household income.

Overall, the hypothesis that socioeconomic variables like median household income would be most strongly correlated with the poor health index was confirmed by both the performed exploratory data analysis and an analysis of the trained decision tree. Additionally, these socioeconomic variables are correlated with the behavioral variables of a county that are more traditionally thought of as contributors to a healthy lifestyle.
